Apply the various steps involved to get cookie value using server-side scripting.

SOLUTION:
Steps to Get Cookie Value in PHP:
1. Create a cookie with setcookie()
This sends a cookie to the browser.
Example:
setcookie("username", "JohnDoe", time() + 3600, "/"); 

2. Browser stores the cookie
The cookie will be available until it expires (1 hour here).
It is automatically sent back to the server with each request.

3. Access cookie on the server using $_COOKIE
PHP stores all cookies in the global associative array $_COOKIE.
Example:
if (isset($_COOKIE['username'])) {
    echo "Cookie Value: " . $_COOKIE['username'];
} else {
    echo "Cookie not set yet!";
}

4. Important Note
The cookie will be available only after the next page load (because cookies are set in the response header).
Always call setcookie() before any HTML output, otherwise PHP will throw a headers already sent error.

CODE:
<?php
// Step 1: Create a cookie
setcookie("username", "JohnDoe", time() + 3600, "/"); // 1 hour validity

// Step 2: Access the cookie
if (isset($_COOKIE['username'])) {
    echo "Welcome back, " . $_COOKIE['username'] . "!";
} else {
    echo "Cookie not set yet. Please refresh the page.";
}
?>
